{"title_page": "David Balmer", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=David Balmer\n| image name=\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=[[Colorado's 27th Senate district|27th]]\n| term_start= January 15, 2013\n| term_end= December 31, 2015\n| preceded= [[Nancy Spence]]\n| succeeded= [[Jack Tate (politician)|Jack Tate]]\n| name2=\n| state_house2=Colorado\n| state2=Colorado\n| district2=39th \n| term_start2= January 2005\n| term_end2= January 2013\n| preceded2= \n| succeeded2= [[Polly Lawrence]]\n| birth_date= \n| birth_place= \n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse= Karen\n| profession= Consultant\n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''David Balmer''' is a former legislator in the U.S. of State of [[Colorado]]. Elected to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] in 2005, he won election to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2012. In late 2015, he resigned his seat representing [[Colorado's 27th Senate district|Senate District 27]] which encompasses parts of [[Arapahoe County, Colorado|Arapahoe County]].\n\n==Biography and early career==\n\nFrom 1994\u20132008, he served in various positions with Cherokee Investment Partners, the nation\u2019s largest private equity firm specializing in brownfield redevelopment. Cherokee has purchased over 300 contaminated sites across North America and Europe. Cherokee closed its Denver office in 2008. As a Lt. Colonel in the U.S. Army Reserve, David served in deployments to [[Afghanistan]] and [[Bosnia]].\n\n===2010 election===\nIn 2010, Balmer ran for re-election to House District 39. He faced Carol Levine as his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, and defeated her with 61.1% of the votes.<ref name=\"2010general\">{{cite news |url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-house/2010/\n|work=Denver Post |accessdate=2012-11-29 }}</ref>\n\n===2011 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Balmer\n|Year=2011\n|Bill Number 1=HB 11-1065\n|Bill Number 2=HB 11-1140\n|Bill Number 3=HB 11-1162\n|Bill Number 4=SB 11-054\n|Bill Number 5=SB 11-255\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9F1A149B68A8B5E987257801006051F7?Open&file=1065_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/087EFDDE5C04CD07872578080080ECB8?Open&file=1140_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/DE11A55E4D0AD8F587257815002712FC?Open&file=1162_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/8B6D1125F38FFB8F87257808008040E1?Open&file=054_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/B3AFA9184D0E5454872578530055CA79?Open&file=255_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 3=Vote failed in House committee \n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1= Concerning restrictions on the appearance by public officials in communications paid for with state moneys.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning measures to strengthen the enforcement of laws against illegal aliens.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the reinstatement of the state sales and use tax exemption for soft drinks.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning the authority of law enforcement officers to arrest unlawfully present aliens.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning the collection of charitable solicitations from passing motorists on a public roadway by local government public safety personnel.\n}}\nBalmer sponsored several measures during the 2011 legislative session, one of which looked to reinstate sales tax exemptions on soft drinks. HB 11-1162 would have given soft drink retailers exemption from the state sales and use tax. The bill passed through the House Finance Committee before the House Appropriations Committee, where the final action to vote failed.\n\nBalmer also headed legislation that would have prohibited current elected officials from being featured in public ads paid for with state funds. The bill passed through the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] before being sent to the Senate, where it was assigned to the Senate State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee. The bill was put to a vote, but failed to pass on a 3\u20132 party-line vote.\n\n===2012 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Balmer\n|Year=2012\n|Bill Number 1=HB 12-1016\n|Bill Number 2=HB 12-1098\n|Bill Number 3=HB 12-1117\n|Bill Number 4=HB 12-1332\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/C4EDAF40BE71BDC987257981007DCDB9?Open&file=1016_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/51F8AED5DCC9524887257981007F11A7?Open&file=1098_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1E7564827B02943187257981007F0C28?Open&file=1117_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/6F5CFB5465F9D7EB87257981007F580E?Open&file=1332_enr.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 4= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]] \n|Bill Title 1= Concerning limiting ex parte communications by commissioners of the public utilities commission.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the sale of motor vehicles that have been damaged to such an extent that the cost of the repairs exceeds the fair market value of the vehicle.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the ability of a local government to permit the collection of charitable solicitations from motorists on a certain number of days per year.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning licensure of anesthesiologist assistants. \n}}\n\n==Colorado State Senate==\n\n===2012 election===\n\nAfter being term-limited in the [[Colorado House of Representatives]], Balmer ran for the Senate seat left open by Senator [[Nancy Spence]] who was also term-limited. Balmer ran for election to the [[Colorado Senate]] for district 27. He faced no opposition during the primaries, but faced Democratic opponent [[David Paladino]] during the general election. Balmer won election to the State Senate with 55.3% of the vote and over 7,000 votes more than his opponent.<ref name=\"2012general\">{{cite news |url=http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2012/|work=Denver Post |accessdate=2012-11-09 }}</ref>\n\n===2013 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=Balmer\n|Year=2013\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Number 6=\n|Bill Link 1=\n|Bill Link 2= \n|Bill Link 3= \n|Bill Link 4= \n|Bill Link 5= \n|Bill Link 6= \n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2= \n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Status 6=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5=\n|Bill Title 6= \n}}\n\nFor the 2013 legislative session, Senator Balmer was appointed to the Business, Labor, and Technology Committee, and the Local Government Committee.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2013A/cslFrontPages.nsf/HomeSplash?OpenForm Colorado General Assembly Website]\n* [http://coloradosenatenews.com/ Colorado Senate News]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balmer, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=David Balmer\n| image name=\n